Battle Frontier Pokémon

The following Pokémon are used in the Battle Frontier. Every individual species used by these facilities can have between one and ten movesets associated with them. There are roughly four groups of 'power levels' of species that can be encountered:

  1. Low Tier: Consists largely of first-stage Pokémon and some weak evolved Pokémon. Species in this tier have one set associated with them. There are two groups listed below: the first group will never appear in the Battle Factory.
  2. Mid Tier: Consists largely of middle-stage Pokémon and some weak fully evolved Pokémon. Species in this tier have two sets associated with them.
  3. High Tier: Consists largely of fully-evolved Pokémon. The majority of species in this tier have four sets associated with them; a select few (strong Pokémon, like Gengar, Salamence, and Metagross) have eight sets, with the first four appearing in the High Tier and the last four appearing in the Legend Tier.
  4. Legend Tier: Contains all Legendaries that are legal in the Battle Frontier, as well as Dragonite and Tyranitar. The last four sets of the strong High Tier Pokémon are also contained here. Dragonite and Tyranitar have ten sets; legendaries except for Latias and Latios have six sets; and Latias and Latios have eight sets.

Pokémon seen in the Battle Tents are pulled from a different set of Pokémon than those used by the Frontier. See each of the Battle Tents' pages for details on those facilities' Pokémon.

The common way of referring to a Pokémon with multiple sets is to identify the set with a number, e.g. "Set2 Rayquaza", "Rayquaza1", or "Rayquaza-3". For my tables, I will be using the "Rayquaza-1" method of referring to sets.

Battle Frontier Set Mechanics

In any Battle Frontier facility, any enemy Trainer the player faces, apart from the Frontier Brain, will be pulled from a pre-existing list of 300 Trainers. Each Trainer has a roster of Pokémon and an IV value associated with them, and the game will choose three random Pokémon from their roster to make the player battle. The roster and IVs are identical in both Level 50 and Open Level modes, except in the Battle Factory (discussed below). The chosen Pokémon will never be the same species or have the same held item as each other. The Trainers page gives more detail and shows each Trainer's roster.

The first 220 Trainers on the list are split into seven groups, where each group can only use one set of Pokémon from a specific tier. Trainers 221-300 have some Trainers that can use Pokémon from multiple sets, as well as the Legend Tier, and a few of them use some Set-2 Mid Tier Pokémon as well.

The number of battles the player has participated in will determine which Trainers can be selected as enemies, and therefore, which sets of Pokémon the player might face. The progression proceeds as follows:

  • Battles 1-6: Low Tier (both groups), 3IV
  • Battle 7: Set-1 Mid Tier, 6IV
  • Battles 8-13: Low Tier (both groups), 3IV or Set-1 Mid Tier, 6IV
  • Battle 14: Set-2 Mid Tier, 9IV
  • Battles 15-20: Set-1, 6IV or Set-2, 9IV Mid Tier
  • Battle 21: Set-1 High Tier, 12IV
  • Battles 22-27: Set-2 Mid Tier, 9IV or Set-1, 12IV High Tier
  • Battle 28: Set-2 High Tier, 15IV
  • Battles 29-34: Set-1, 12IV or Set-2, 15IV High Tier
  • Battle 35: Set-3 High Tier, 18IV
  • Battles 36-41: Set-2, 15IV or Set-3, 18IV High Tier
  • Battle 42: Set-4 High Tier, 21IV
  • Battles 43-48: Set-3, 18IV or Set-4, 21IV High Tier
  • Battle 49: Any High or Legend Tier, with a few Set-2 Mid Tier Pokémon, 31IV
  • Battles 50+: Any High or Legend Tier, with a few Set-2 Mid Tier Pokémon, 21IV or 31IV

A bug in the Battle Dome means that all Pokémon, except those used by Tucker, always have 3IV.

Battle Factory Set Mechanics

In this facility, the same set of 300 Trainers can be chosen as enemies, but they will not use the roster associated with them. They will instead use a random set of Pokémon chosen from a specific tier, depending on the mode (Level 50 or Open Level). Their IVs are tied to the battle number instead of the Trainer.

The seventh Trainer of every round of seven battles will use the same tier of Pokémon as the preceding Trainers, but will have the IV values associated with the following round.

I say all this about the IVs, but a programming error actually causes the game to check for the player's current Battle Tower streak, instead of Factory, when generating Trainers' teams. This means that the enemy Trainers' IVs can, for instance, always be kept at 3 so long as the player has no streak in the Battle Tower. The exception is the Frontier Brain Noland, who always has 15 IVs in his first battle and 31 in his second.

The IV and tier progression is shown below.

Battles IVs Level 50 Open Level
1-7 3 Low Tier (Group 2), as well as Mid Tier Set-1 up to and including Furret-1 Set-1 High Tier
8-14 6 Set-1 Mid Tier Set-2 High Tier
15-21 9 Set-2 Mid Tier Set-3 High Tier
22-28 12 Set-1 High Tier Set-4 High Tier
29-35 15 Set-2 High Tier Any High or Legend Tier
36-42 21 Set-3 High Tier Any High or Legend Tier
43-49 31 Set-4 High Tier Any High or Legend Tier
50+ 31 Any High or Legend Tier, except for Dragonite, Tyranitar,
the Legendary Birds' 5th and 6th sets,
and the Legendary Beasts' 5th and 6th sets		 Any High or Legend Tier

This progression is identical to the one that controls which Pokémon the player can choose at the start of every round of seven. However, there are two differences from how Trainers' Pokémon are generated:

  1. The glitch that affects the IVs of the enemy Trainers' Pokémon does not apply to the Trainers.
  2. One or more Pokémon may be 'upgraded', meaning it will be replaced with a Pokémon from the next tier, and its IVs will increase. Whether Pokémon are upgraded depends on how many swaps the player has made; see the Battle Factory page for more info. The progression of upgraded Pokémon is shown below.
Battle(s) Level 50 Upgraded Open Level Upgraded
1-7 N/A N/A
8-14 N/A N/A
15-21 N/A N/A
22-28 Set-2 High Tier, 15IV Any High or Legend Tier, 15IV
29-35 Set-3 High Tier, 21IV Any High or Legend Tier, 21IV
36-42 Set-4 High Tier, 31IV Any High or Legend Tier, 31IV
43-49 Any High or Legend Tier (except for Dragonite, Tyranitar,
the Legendary Birds' 5th and 6th sets,
and the Legendary Beasts' 5th and 6th sets), 31IV		 Any High or Legend Tier, 31IV

After battle 50, the player can see any High or Legend Tier Pokémon (except for those that will never be seen in Level 50), and they will always have 31 IVs. This goes for both regularly genereated Pokémon and upgrades, meaning there is functionally no difference between a regular Pokémon and an upgraded one.
